# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metal-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The **Apple A11 Bionic** is a 64-bit ARM-based system on a chip (SoC) designed by Apple Inc., part of the Apple silicon series, and manufactured by TSMC.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] It was only used in the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus, and iPhone X which were introduced on September 12, 2017.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] Apple states that the two high-performance cores are 25% faster than the Apple A10's and the four high-efficiency cores are up to 70% faster than the two corresponding cores in the A10.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 Bionic chip was discontinued on April 15, 2020, following the discontinuation of the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The latest software update for the iPhone 8 & 8 Plus and iPhone X using this chip was iOS 16.7.15, released on March 11th, 2026.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 features an Apple-designed 64-bit ARMv8-A six-core CPU, with two high-performance cores at 2.39 GHz, called **Monsoon**, and four energy-efficient cores, called **Mistral**.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The Monsoon cores are a 7-wide decode out-of-order superscalar design, while the Mistral cores are a 3-wide decode out-of-order superscalar design.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The Mistral cores are based on Apple's Swift cores from the Apple A6.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 uses a new second-generation performance controller, which permits the A11 to use all six cores simultaneously, unlike its predecessor the A10.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 also integrates an Apple-designed three-core graphics processing unit (GPU) with 30% faster graphics performance than the A10.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] Embedded in the A11 is the M11 motion coprocessor.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 includes a new image processor which supports computational photography functions such as lighting estimation, wide color capture, and advanced pixel processing.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 is manufactured by TSMC using a 10 nm FinFET process and contains 4.3 billion transistors on a die 87.66 mm2 in size, 30% smaller than the A10.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] It is manufactured in a package on package (PoP) together with 2 GB of LPDDR4X memory in the iPhone 8 and 3 GB of LPDDR4X memory in the iPhone 8 Plus and iPhone X.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 has video codec encoding support for HEVC and H.264.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] It has decoding support for HEVC, H.264, MPEG‑4 Part 2, and Motion JPEG.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The A11 also includes dedicated neural network hardware that Apple calls a "Neural Engine".
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] This neural network hardware can perform up to 600 billion operations per second and is used for Face ID, Animoji and other machine learning tasks.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The neural engine allows Apple to implement neural network and machine learning in a more energy-efficient manner than using either the main CPU or the GPU.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] However, third-party apps cannot use the Neural Engine, leading to similar neural network performance to older iPhones.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] Bloomberg says that the neural engine is the fruit of Apple's efforts to improve its AI team, since the 2015 report by Bloomberg states that Apple's secretive nature made it difficult to attract AI research scientists.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] Apple has since recruited people and multiple companies working on AI, and has published papers related to AI research.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] In October 2016, Apple hired Russ Salakhutdinov as its director of AI research.
[src:metal-api/apple-a11] The Apple A11 Bionic chip is used in the following iPhone models and not on any generation of iPad, iPod touch, or Apple TV.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:metal-api/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal is an object-oriented API that can be invoked using the Swift, Objective-C or C++17 programming languages.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Full-blown GPU execution is controlled via the Metal Shading Language.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal aims to provide low-overhead access to the GPU.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Commands are encoded beforehand and then submitted to the GPU for asynchronous execution.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] The application controls when to wait for the execution to complete thus allowing application developers to increase throughput by encoding other commands while commands are executed on the GPU or save power by explicitly waiting for GPU execution to complete.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Additionally, command encoding is CPU independent thus applications can encode commands to each CPU thread independently.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Lastly, render states are pre-computed beforehand, allowing the GPU driver to know in advance how to configure and optimize the render pipeline before command execution.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal improves the capabilities of GPGPU programming by using compute shaders.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal uses a specific shading language based on C++14, implemented using Clang and LLVM.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal allows application developers to create Metal resources such as buffers and textures.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Resources can be allocated on the CPU, GPU, or both and provides facilities to update and synchronize allocated resources.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal can also enforce a resource's state during a command encoder's lifetime.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] On macOS, Metal can provide application developers the discretion to specify which GPU to execute.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Application developers can choose between the low-power integrated GPU of the CPU, the discrete GPU (on certain MacBooks and Macs) or an external GPU connected through Thunderbolt.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal Performance Shaders is a highly optimized library of graphics functions that can help application developers achieve great performance at the same time decrease work on maintaining GPU family specific functions.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal has been available since June 2, 2014 on iOS devices powered by Apple A7 or later, and since June 8, 2015 on Macs (2012 models or later) running OS X El Capitan.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] On June 5, 2017, at WWDC, Apple announced the second version of Metal, to be supported by macOS High Sierra, iOS 11 and tvOS 11.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal 2 is not a separate API from Metal and is supported by the same hardware.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal 2 enables more efficient profiling and debugging in Xcode, accelerated machine learning, lower CPU workload, support for virtual reality on macOS, and specificities of the Apple A11 GPU, in particular.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] At the 2020 WWDC, Apple announced the migration of the Mac to Apple silicon.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Macs using Apple silicon will feature Apple GPUs with a feature set combining what was previously available on macOS and iOS, and will be able to take advantage of features tailored to the tile based deferred rendering (TBDR) architecture of Apple GPUs.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] At the 2022 WWDC, Apple announced the third version of Metal (Metal 3), which would debut with the release of macOS Ventura, iOS 16 and iPadOS 16.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Metal 3 introduces the MetalFX upscaling framework, which renders complex scenes in less time per frame with high-performance upscaling and anti-aliasing, mesh shaders support.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Also announced possibility to use C/C++ for Metal API.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] At the 2023 WWDC, Apple announced a brand new toolkit called the Game Porting Toolkit to port Windows 10/11-based games.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] It includes an environment to test binaries, translation layers from HLSL to MSL, and Metal-cpp bindings.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] Jeremy Sandmel announced a new Game Mode for macOS Sonoma, and Hideo Kojima announced *Death Stranding* for the macOS App Store.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] At the 2024 WWDC, Apple announced Game Porting Toolkit 2, along with the release of new games such as *Control: Ultimate Edition*, *Frostpunk 2*, and *Assassin's Creed Shadows* for macOS.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] At the 2025 WWDC, Apple announced Metal 4, a new version of the API featuring a unified command encoder system, support for neural rendering, and new technologies such as MetalFX Frame Interpolation and a ray tracing denoiser.
[src:metal-api/metal-api] According to Apple, more than 148,000 applications use Metal directly, and 1.7 million use it through high-level frameworks, as of June 2017. macOS games using Metal for rendering are listed below.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] A **shading language** is a graphics programming language made for programming shader effects on the graphics processing unit (unlike other programming languages, which send instructions to the central processing unit instead).
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Because of this, shading languages are usually more 'low level' languages and usually consist of special data types like "vector", "matrix", "color" and "normal".
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Shading languages used in offline rendering tend to be close to natural language, so that no special knowledge of programming is required.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Offline rendering aims to produce maximum-quality images, at the cost of greater time and compute than real-time rendering.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The RenderMan Shading Language (RSL or SL, for short), defined in the *RenderMan Interface Specification*, is a common shading language for production-quality rendering.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] It is also one of the first shading languages ever implemented.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Houdini VEX (Vector Expressions) shading language (often abbreviated to "VEX") is closely modeled after RenderMan.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] However, its integration into a complete 3D package means that the shader writer can access the information inside the shader, a feature that is not usually available in a rendering context.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The language differences between RSL and VEX are mainly syntactic, in addition to differences regarding the names of several shadeop names.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Gelato's shading language, like Houdini's VEX, is closely modeled after RenderMan.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The differences between Gelato Shading Language and RSL are mainly syntactical — Gelato uses semicolons instead of commas to separate arguments in function definitions and a few shadeops have different names and parameters.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Open Shading Language (OSL) was developed by Sony Pictures Imageworks for use in its Autodesk Arnold Renderer.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] It is also used by Blender's Cycles render engine.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] OSL's surface and volume shaders define how surfaces or volumes scatter light in a way that allows for importance sampling; thus, it is well suited for physically-based renderers that support ray tracing and global illumination.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Shading languages for real-time rendering are now widespread.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] They provide both higher hardware abstraction and a more flexible programming model than previous paradigms, which hardcoded transformation and shading equations.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] They deliver more control and richer content with less overhead.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Shaders that are designed to be executed directly on the GPU became useful for high-throughput general processing because of their stream programming model; this led to the development of compute shaders running on similar hardware (see also: GPGPU).
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Historically, a few such languages dominated the market; they are described below.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board established the ARB assembly language in 2002 as a standard low-level instruction set for programmable graphics processors.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] High-level OpenGL shading languages often compile to ARB assembly for loading and execution.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Unlike high-level shading languages, ARB assembly does not support control flow or branching.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] However, it continues to be used when cross-GPU portability is required.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Also known as GLSL or *glslang*, this standardized shading language is meant to be used with OpenGL.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The language unifies vertex and fragment processing in a single instruction set, allowing conditional loops and branches.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] GLSL was preceded by the ARB assembly language.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The Cg language, developed by Nvidia, was designed for easy and efficient production pipeline integration.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] It features API independence and comes with many free tools to improve asset management.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Development of Cg was stopped in 2012, and the language is now deprecated.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The shader assembly language in Direct3D 8 and 9 is the main programming language for vertex and pixel shaders in Shader Model 1.0/1.1, 2.0, and 3.0.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] It is a direct representation of the intermediate shader bytecode which is passed to the graphics driver for execution.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The shader assembly language cannot be directly used to program unified Shader Model 4.0, 4.1, 5.0, and 5.1, although it retains its function as a representation of the intermediate bytecode for debug purposes.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] The High-Level Shading Language (HLSL) is a C-style shader language for DirectX 9 and higher and Xbox game consoles.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] It is related to Nvidia's Cg, but is only supported by DirectX and Xbox.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] HLSL programs are compiled into bytecode equivalent of DirectX shader assembly language.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] HLSL was introduced as an optional alternative to the shader assembly language in Direct3D 9, but became a requirement in Direct3d 10 and higher, where the shader assembly language is deprecated.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Adobe Systems added Pixel Bender as part of the Adobe Flash 10 API.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Pixel Bender could only process pixel but not 3D-vertex data.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Flash 11 introduced an entirely new 3D API called Stage3D, which uses its own shading language called Adobe Graphics Assembly Language (AGAL), which offers full 3D acceleration support.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] GPU acceleration for Pixel Bender was removed in Flash 11.8.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] AGAL is a low-level but platform-independent shading language, which can be compiled, for example, to the ARB assembly language or GLSL.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Sony announced PlayStation Shader Language (PSSL) as a shading language similar to Cg/HLSL, but specific to the PlayStation 4.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] PSSL is said to be largely compatible with the HLSL shader language from DirectX 12, but with additional features for the PS4 and PS5 platforms.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Apple has created a low-level graphics API, called Metal, which runs on most Macs made since 2012, iPhones since the 5S, and iPads since the iPad Air.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] Metal has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language (MSL), which is based on C++14 and implemented using clang and LLVM.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] MSL unifies vertex, fragment and compute processing.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL) is the shader language for WebGPU.
[src:metal-api/shading-language] That is, an application using the WebGPU API uses WGSL to express the programs, known as shaders, that run on the GPU.
